Gibbs Sampling

  1. Select starting values x0x0 and set t=0t=0
  2. Generate in turn (deterministic scan Gibbs sampler)
    • x(1)t+1∼f(x(1)|x(−1)t)xt+1(1)∼f(x(1)|xt(−1))
    • x(2)t+1∼f(x(2)|x(1)t+1,x(3)t,,x(p)t)xt+1(2)∼f(x(2)|xt+1(1),xt(3),,xt(p))
    • x(3)t+1∼f(x(3)|x(1)t+1,x(2)t+1,x(4)t,,x(p)t)xt+1(3)∼f(x(3)|xt+1(1),xt+1(2),xt(4),,xt(p))
    • x(p)t+1∼f(x(p)|x(−p)t+1)xt+1(p)∼f(x(p)|xt+1(−p))
  3. Increment tt and go to Step 2

Gibbs Sampling

  • Common to have one or more components not available in closed form
  • Then one can just use a MH sampler for those components known as a Metropolis within Gibbs or Hybrid Gibbs sampling
  • Common to ``block'' groups of random variables

  • Data from a fur seal pup capture-recapture study for i=7i=7 census attempts
  • Goal is to estimate the number of pups in a fur seal colony using a capture-recapture study

Newly Caught mimi 30 8 17 7 9 8 5

Example: Capture-recapture

  • Let NN be the population size, II be the number of census attempts where cici were captured (I=7I=7 in our case), and rr be the total number captured (r=∑Ii=1mi=84r=∑i=1Imi=84)

  • We consider a separate unknown capture probability for each census (α1,,αI)(α1,,αI) where the animals are equally ``catchable''

  • Then

    L(N,α|c,r)∝N!(N−r)!∏i=1Iαcii(1−αi)N−ciL(N,α|c,r)∝N!(N−r)!∏i=1Iαici(1−αi)N−ci

Example: Capture-recapture

  • Assume NN and αα are apriori independent with
    f(N)∝1 and f(αi|θ1,θ2)∼i.i.d.Beta(θ1,θ2)f(N)∝1 and f(αi|θ1,θ2)∼i.i.d.Beta(θ1,θ2)
  • We use θ1=θ2=1/2θ1=θ2=1/2, which is the Jeffrey's Prior
  • The resulting posterior is proper when I>2I>2 and recommended when I>5I>5

Example: Capture-recapture

  • Then it is easy to show the posterior is
    f(N,α|c,r)∝N!(N−r)!∏i=1Iαcii(1−αi)N−ci∏i=1Iα−1/2i(1−αi)−1/2.f(N,α|c,r)∝N!(N−r)!∏i=1Iαici(1−αi)N−ci∏i=1Iαi−1/2(1−αi)−1/2.
  • Further, one can show
    N−84|ααi|N∼NB(85,1−∏i=1I(1−αi)) and ∼Beta(ci+1/2,N−ci+1/2) for all iN−84|α∼NB(85,1−∏i=1I(1−αi)) and αi|N∼Beta(ci+1/2,N−ci+1/2) for all i

Example: Capture-recapture

Then we can consider the chain

(N,α)→(N′,α)→(N′,α′)(N,α)→(N′,α)→(N′,α′)
or
(N,α)→(N,α′)→(N′,α′),(N,α)→(N,α′)→(N′,α′),
where both involve a ``block'' update of αα

Example: Capture-recapture

First, we can write the data into R

captured <- c(30, 22, 29, 26, 31, 32, 35)
new.captures <- c(30, 8, 17, 7, 9, 8, 5)
total.r <- sum(new.captures)

Example: Capture-recapture

The following R code implements the Gibbs sampler

gibbs.chain <- function(n, N.start = 94, alpha.start = rep(.5,7)) {
    output <- matrix(0, nrow=n, ncol=8)
    for(i in 1:n){
        neg.binom.prob <- 1 - prod(1-alpha.start)
        N.new <- rnbinom(1, 85, neg.binom.prob) + total.r
        beta1 <- captured + .5
        beta2 <- N.new - captured + .5
        alpha.new <- rbeta(7, beta1, beta2)
        output[i,] <- c(N.new, alpha.new)
        N.start <- N.new
        alpha.start <- alpha.new    
    }
    return(output)
}

MCMC output analysis

How can we tell if the chain is mixing well?

  • Trace plots or time-series plots
  • Autocorrelation plots
  • Plot of estimate versus Markov chain sample size
  • Effective sample size (ESS)
    ESS(n)=n1+2∑∞k=1ρk(g),ESS(n)=n1+2∑k=1∞ρk(g),
    where ρk(g)ρk(g) is the autocorrelation of lag kk for gg
  • Alternative, ESS can be written as
    ESS(n)=nσ2/VargESS(n)=nσ2/Varg
    where σ2σ2 is the asymptotic variance from a Markov chain CLT

Example: Capture-recapture

Then we consider some preliminary simulations to ensure the chain is mixing well

trial <- gibbs.chain(1000)
plot.ts(trial[,1], main = "Trace Plot for N")
for(i in 1:7){
    plot.ts(trial[,(i+1)], main = paste("Alpha", i))
    }

acf(trial[,1], main = "Lag Plot for N")
for(i in 1:7){
    acf(trial[,(i+1)], main = paste("Lag Alpha", i))
    }

Convergence diagnostics

  • A more popular method of MCMC output analysis
  • There are many; Gelman and Rubin diagnostic, Geweke's diagnostic, Heidel diagnostic, Raferty diagnostic, and other in coda package
  • Useful to detect problem with a sampler, but offer no guarantee you have converged
  • Think of these like hypothesis testing

Gelman and Rubin diagnostic

Gelman and Rubin Diagnostic is also used a stopping criteria

  • Most popular method for stopping the simulation, one of many convergence diagnostics
  • Simulates mm independent parallel Markov chains
  • Considers a ratio of two different estimates of VarπgVarπg, not σ2gσg2 from the CLT
  • Argue the simulation should continue until the diagnostic (R0.975R^0.975) is close to 1

Toy example

  • Let Y1,,YmY1,,Ym be i.i.d. N(μ,λ)N(μ,λ) and let the prior for (μ,λ)(μ,λ) be proportional to 1/λ−−√1/λ
  • The posterior density is characterized by
    π(μ,λ|y)∝λ−m+12exp{−12λ∑j=1m(yj−μ)2}π(μ,λ|y)∝λ−m+12exp⁡{−12λ∑j=1m(yj−μ)2}
    which is proper as long as m≥3m≥3

Toy example

  • A Gibbs sampler requires the full conditionals
    μ|λ,y∼N(y,λ/m)μ|λ,y∼N(y,λ/m)
    and
    λ|μ,y∼IG(m−12,s2+m(y−μ)22),λ|μ,y∼IG(m−12,s2+m(y−μ)22),
    where yy is the sample mean and s2=∑(yi−y)2s2=∑(yi−y)2

Toy example

  • Consider the Gibbs sampler that updates λλ then μμ
    (λ′,μ′)→(λ,μ′)→(λ,μ)(λ′,μ′)→(λ,μ′)→(λ,μ)
  • This sampler is geometrically ergodic
  • Suppose m=11m=11, y=1y=1, and s2=14s2=14
  • Then E(μ|y)=1E(μ|y)=1 and E(λ|y)=2E(λ|y)=2
  • Consider estimating E(μ|y)E(μ|y) and E(λ|y)E(λ|y) with μnμn and λnλn

Summary

  • Bayesian inference usually requires a MCMC simulation
  • Metropolis-Hastings algorithm and Gibbs samplers
  • Basic idea is similar to OMC, but sampling from a Markov chain yields dependent draws
  • MCMC output analysis is often ignored or poorly understood
